Happy Valentine's Day! This is my engagement picture (taken in 1984). It's hard to believe I've shared such a huge part of my life with this one person. The years have passed in the blink of an eye! Ted and I both have our faults, but the glue that has held us together all these years is his capacity for love, his generosity in love and his ability to show love when I need it most. He has the kindest heart on the planet, and I'm lucky he's been willing to trust me with it. I can't wait to hit the road with him on April 11th to start our big traveling bookstore tour for THE SEASIDE LIBRARY. We'll be driving every day for nearly two months! When we planned this, we laughed and said, "It's a good thing we enjoy being together." Ain't that the truth!

Not many husbands would be willing to take two months off work to drive their wife to thirty-two book signings across the country, but Ted isn’t just any husband. He helps me edit every book I write by listening to me read each manuscript aloud as we drive to some fun location—Lake Tahoe, Yosemite, the Redwoods, Napa, San Francisco or Santa Cruz. We enjoy stopping to eat and making a fun trip out of it. So when I suggested a cross-country tour with a traveling bookstore, he didn’t hesitate to get behind the idea one-hundred percent. He even offered to create his own signature drinks to offer to those who come to the signings to add another level of fun—so we put a small coffee shop in Brenda Novak’s Bookstream. After doing all the research on which automatic espresso machine would be able to do everything he needed, he chose a Jura. Now he’s working on perfecting his signature drink! This story is about three friends who’ve grown up together and vowed to protect each other even if it means lying for a teenaged Cam when he becomes the prime suspect in a missing persons case. Ariana and Ivy believe they did the right thing until, twenty years later, new evidence emerges on the case. Day ONE on the road for THE SEASIDE LIBRARY Book Tour: Even after all the planning that’s gone into being gone for two months, it took forever to pack up. On Sunday a very late night turned into an early morning, and still we didn’t get off until 2:00 p.m. By then we were packed so tightly we couldn’t fit even one more item. Problem was…we still had to pick up Alexa. After we squished and squashed and utilized every nook and cranny, we had her shoved in and were off on our wild adventure. 

On Monday we arrived in Sausalito—miraculously—on time. After rolling in at 5:00 p.m., an hour early, we met quite a few people who were already there waiting for us. One reader came all the way from New Jersey! While Ted got his coffee shop set up, I greeted New York Times bestselling author @catherinecoulterauthor, who was my conversation partner for this stop, and Cheryl Pop, the owner of @sausalitobooks. Chef Mike from @z.cioccolato was there from San Francisco with delicious fudge samples. We showed people through the Bookstream, Ted made his fabulous drinks (my new fav is his Mayan hot chocolate!), Catherine and I spoke, we took questions and did a few giveaways and then it was time to say good-bye. Because Vinny surprised Alexa by driving two hours to attend the event despite having to go right back and be to work early in the morning, we took the time to have dinner with him at @poggiotrattoria, a delicious Italian restaurant right across the street. That part was fun, but the next part wasn’t. We didn’t leave for San Diego until almost 11:00 p.m.! Fortunately, we managed to talk a Hilton in Carlsbad into letting us arrive at 7:00 a.m. so we could sleep all day and be rested for the event. 
#bookstagram #bookstream #sausalito

Day TWO on the road for THE SEASIDE LIBRARY Book Tour: After driving all night Monday night, we got in the jacuzzi at the hotel in Carlsbad, which felt like heaven. It was release day, so that was our little celebration—all we could manage because we desperately needed sleep. After a three-hour nap, we had to get ready because I was going to get to have dinner with one of my idols—New York Times bestselling author @sepauthor! I was reading Susan’s books (HEAVEN, TEXAS, NOBODY’S BABY BUT MINE and AIN’T SHE SWEET are some of my favs) long before I was ever published. I’d attend Romance Writers of America’s annual convention and arrange my schedule specifically around the times she’d be speaking. It was when I was sitting in one of her workshops that I had an epiphany on one of my earliest books and rushed out of the room after it was over to get beyond the writer’s block that’d been crippling me on that manuscript. In another of her workshops, she talked about authors having a “core story” or reoccurring theme that is an extension of their world view, and that was when I was able to identify the themes of forgiveness and redemption that show up so often in my work. So you can imagine just how excited I was to get to know her better; it was my first opportunity to go out with her and speak privately for any length of time.

We had the best Mexican food I’d tasted in a long time (and living in California, I get a lot of good Mexican food) at @eatpuesto.

Julie and the rest of the staff at @warwicksbooks did a fabulous job of hosting the event. They had a place cordoned off in back for the Bookstream, and Ted got right to work making drinks. As SEP and I spoke about our writing lives and our current books. We ended the event by toasting my new release with Marinelli’s in some darling branded wine glasses Alexa had made for the occasion. Here’s to the release of my 75th book and SEP and so many readers coming to celebrate with me!

We left Warwick’s about eleven—it always takes longer to pack up than we think—and headed straight to Vegas. 
#bookstagram #booksigning #bookstream #bookbirthday

Day THREE on the road for THE SEASIDE LIBRARY Book Tour: Despite the fact that I was running on almost no sleep (for several days in a row), Vegas was a blast. I love that warm, bustling desert city! It was such a treat to have New York Times bestselling author @raeannethayne join me there. She came all the way from a small town north of Salt Lake City—flew in just for this event—and I got to enjoy a late lunch with her at a small Italian restaurant called @amanolasvegas that serves “fat babies”—giant open-ended rolls filled with spaghetti and meatballs and topped with cheese—which were spectacular. I had no idea we were going to view an autopsy that day, but a man had just been stabbed in a bar in Sacramento the night before, and they were currently performing an autopsy on him that we were invited to watch. I was grateful for the opportunity, because I knew it would be fabulous for research purposes, so I immediately agreed, and I thought I was handling it just fine. I wasn’t only watching, I was asking questions—until my autonomic nervous system started shutting down. I didn’t pass out, but I nearly did. I slid down the wall and ended up on the floor, and it took at least a half hour before I had the strength to get on my feet again. I was so embarrassed that I couldn’t tolerate it, especially because everyone else handled it so well. LOL

Day SEVEN on the road for THE SEASIDE LIBRARY Book Tour: How I roll before an event—notice the shoes. 😂

Before we left Santa Fe for Albuquerque, we managed to do some shopping in the old town square. There was Native American jewelry and other items displayed on blankets all the way down a very long sidewalk in front of a pueblo-style building built in the early 1600s. I could’ve spent all day pouring over those items. I bought a handmade brass ornament of a pueblo as a keepsake (I collect ornaments so this will show up on my tree in December). Then I crossed the street and purchased some handmade earrings before we had to rush off for Albuquerque.

We arrived in Albuquerque in plenty of time for our event, where we talked about all the changes in publishing over the years (among other things). After two and a half decades in this business, I’ve seen a few twists and turns—from the revolution caused by the internet to the “death” of the indie bookstore to the advent and heyday of self-publishing to the near demise of the writer’s organization that helped me build my career to the “resurrection” of the indie bookstore to the “death” of the mass market paperback, which is where we are now. There is only one thing that never changes in publishing—and that is the constant state of change. 

I owe a big thank you to @booksonthebosque for hosting me. They somehow arranged for perfect weather—the best we’ve had so far—and we had a lovely group attend the event. Four readers drove six hours to come—all the way from Colorado! One of them won a $25 gift certificate they used for a fabulous T-shirt the store was selling. It said, “Powered by plants and books,” which made me notice it, so then I wanted to purchase it for Ted. He’s not a gardener, but he’s a plant-based eater (new age name for vegan—ha!), so I thought it would be perfect, and he loved it. Turns out all the treats at the store were vegan, too—the Mexican Wedding Cake Cookies were delicious!

The idea for THE SEASIDE LIBRARY came to me while my daughter and I were visiting Nantucket to interview New York Times bestselling author Nancy Thayer for Brenda Novak's Book Group. Until then, I’d never been, but I absolutely loved it—as well as the idea of how it would change with the various seasons. The idea of getting cut off from the mainland during too much fog or a big storm—to the point that even the supply boats couldn’t get through—was very intriguing to me. So I came up with Mariners Island, a fictitious setting I placed in the same general area, and tried to imagine what it might be like for three friends growing up on such an island, where the summer influx increases the population by tenfold. I decided it would probably be easy to assume everything was transient—that it would come and go like the tides and tourists—and imagined a friendship between three locals, who toughed out the hard months together, would be stronger than most, which is why Ariana and Ivy do what they do for Cam. THE TALK OF COYOTE CANYON features a female driller—a woman working in a man's world—who's trying to put her father out of business as payback for abandoning her when she was young.
